In `MauiProgram.cs`, use conditional compilation or the `AddPlatformSpecific` pattern:

```csharp
public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

#if ANDROID
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();
#elif IOS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();
#elif WINDOWS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();
#endif

    return builder.Build();
}
```

Each platform-specific implementation lives under `Platforms/<platform>/` and is only compiled for that target (via the folder conventions or `.csproj` conditions). This ensures no missing type errors at runtime since only the relevant `#if` branch compiles per target framework.

**Alternative** — if you prefer no `#if` directives in `MauiProgram.cs`, create a partial class or extension method:

```csharp
// In Platforms/Android/PlatformServices.cs
public static partial class PlatformServices
{
    public static partial IServiceCollection AddNotification(this IServiceCollection s)
        => s.AddSingleton<INotificationService, AndroidNotificationService>();
}
```

Then call `builder.Services.AddNotification();` once in shared code. Each platform supplies its own partial implementation, keeping `MauiProgram.cs` clean.
